## Core Design Principles

### 1. Accessibility First

**Standard:** WCAG 2.1 AA minimum

**Requirements:**
- Color contrast ratios: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text
- All interactive elements keyboard accessible
- Semantic HTML structure (proper headings, landmarks, alt text)
- Focus indicators visible and clear
- Text resizable up to 200% without loss of functionality

**Why:** Accessible design is inclusive design. It benefits all users.

---

### 2. Mobile-First Responsive

**Standard:** Fully functional on all viewport sizes

**Breakpoints:**
- Mobile: 375px (iPhone SE)
- Tablet: 768px (iPad Portrait)
- Desktop: 1440px (Standard Monitor)

**Requirements:**
- Touch-friendly tap targets (min 44×44px)
- Readable text without zooming (min 16px)
- No horizontal scrolling on mobile
- Optimized images for each breakpoint

**Why:** Mobile traffic exceeds desktop. Mobile experience must be excellent.

---

### 3. Performance

**Standard:** Fast load times, smooth interactions

**Requirements:**
- 60fps animations (use transform and opacity for animations)
- Self-contained HTML (no external dependencies when possible)
- Optimized assets (compressed images, minimal CSS/JS)
- Progressive enhancement (works without JavaScript)

**Why:** Users abandon slow sites. Performance is a feature.

---

### 4. Visual Hierarchy

**Standard:** Clear information architecture

**Requirements:**
- One primary action per screen/section
- F-pattern or Z-pattern reading flow
- Clear distinction between primary, secondary, tertiary elements
- Adequate whitespace (breathing room)
- Scannable content (headings, lists, short paragraphs)

**Why:** Users scan, they don't read. Hierarchy guides attention.

---

### 5. Consistency

**Standard:** Coherent design language throughout

**Requirements:**
- Consistent spacing system (8px grid recommended)
- Consistent typography scale (modular scale)
- Consistent color usage (primary, secondary, accent)
- Consistent component styling (buttons, cards, forms)
- Consistent interaction patterns

**Why:** Consistency reduces cognitive load. Familiar patterns feel intuitive.

